2026-07-08 | Signal Towers Reachable by Both Stations

Question
Return the number of towers from which a signal can reach both Station P and Station Q.
	Key Insight
Directly checking every cell would require running a DFS/BFS from every tower, leading to O((nm)²).
Instead, reverse the process.
Instead of checking:
		Cell → Station
start from each station and move in the reverse direction.
If a signal normally moves from:
		A → B
	when
		height(B) ≤ height(A)
then in reverse traversal we can move from:
		B → A
	when
		height(A) ≥ height(B)
So during reverse DFS/BFS, we move only to neighboring cells with greater than or equal signal strength.
	Run two traversals:
•	From all cells on the top and left boundaries (Station P).
•	From all cells on the bottom and right boundaries (Station Q).
Any cell visited in both traversals can reach both stations.
	Approach
1.	Create two visited matrices:
			reachP
			reachQ
2.	Run DFS/BFS from:
			- Top row
			- Left column
		to fill reachP.
3.	Run DFS/BFS from:
			- Bottom row
			- Right column
		to fill reachQ.
4.	Count cells where:
			reachP[i][j] && reachQ[i][j]
5.	Return the count.
	Time Complexity
	O(n × m)
	Each cell is visited at most once in each traversal.
	Space Complexity
	O(n × m)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int n, m;
    int dr[4] = {-1, 1, 0, 0};
    int dc[4] = {0, 0, -1, 1};
    void dfs(int r, int c,
             vector<vector<int>>& mat,
             vector<vector<bool>>& vis) {
        vis[r][c] = true;
        for(int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
            int nr = r + dr[k];
            int nc = c + dc[k];
            if(nr < 0 || nr >= n || nc < 0 || nc >= m)
                continue;
            if(vis[nr][nc])
                continue;
            if(mat[nr][nc] >= mat[r][c]) {
                dfs(nr, nc, mat, vis);
            }
        }
    }
    int countCells(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        n = mat.size();
        m = mat[0].size();
        vector<vector<bool>> reachP(n, vector<bool>(m, false));
        vector<vector<bool>> reachQ(n, vector<bool>(m, false));
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(!reachP[i][0])
                dfs(i, 0, mat, reachP);
            if(!reachQ[i][m - 1])
                dfs(i, m - 1, mat, reachQ);
        }
        for(int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
            if(!reachP[0][j])
                dfs(0, j, mat, reachP);
            if(!reachQ[n - 1][j])
                dfs(n - 1, j, mat, reachQ);
        }
        int ans = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
                if(reachP[i][j] && reachQ[i][j])
                    ans++;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		mat =
		[
		  [1,2,2,3],
		  [3,2,3,4],
		  [2,4,5,3],
		  [6,7,1,4]
		]
	Run reverse DFS from:
		Top + Left → reachP
		Bottom + Right → reachQ
	The cells visited in both traversals are counted.
	Output:
		Number of towers that can reach both stations.
